<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920305-0053</DOCNO><DOCID>920305-0053.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Public Service Co. of New Mexico:   Utility Settles All Lawsuits   By Holders for $33 Million</HL><DATE>03/05/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><CO>   PNM</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)EARNINGS (ERN)WESTERN U.S. ELECTRIC UTILITIES (UEW)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>NEW MEXICO (NM)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Public Service Co. of New Mexico, Albuquerque, N.M., saidit agreed to settle all shareholder class-action andderivative lawsuits for $33 million.   The settlement, to be paid by insurers that carry theutility's directors and officers liability coverage, includes$3 million for Public Service New Mexico, which will partlyoffset its litigation costs. As a result of the settlement,the company said it will take a $1.5 million charge,requiring a restatement of 1991 per-share earnings from 36cents to 32 cents.</LP><TEXT>   According to company documents, the first shareholder suitwas filed in September 1989 in U.S. District Court in NewMexico. Later, a second holder joined the suit. The suitalleged breaches in fiduciary duties, mismanagement and wasteby 11 current or former directors and officers. The suit saidthey caused the company to make questionable investments andexposed it to liability for securities fraud.   The pact was reached after all parties consented to thejurisdiction of Judge Harry McCue of U.S. District Court ofSouthern California for the purpose of settlement talks.</TEXT></DOC>